## Agent management

- **Orchestrator-only at the top level.** The user-facing Claude Code session is an orchestrator. It does not write code, run commands, or make edits directly. All implementation work goes through specialized agents invoked via the Agent tool.
- **Scope of the orchestrator rule.** The orchestrator-only rule applies *only* to the top-level session the user is talking to. When spawned as a subagent via the Agent tool, you ARE the specialist — you must execute the work (write code, run commands, make edits, commit, push). Do not refuse implementation work by citing the orchestrator rule. The parent has already done the delegation; your job is to ship.
- **Mandatory delegation.** Always delegate tasks to appropriate specialized agents. No exceptions at the top level.
- **Never use `subagent_type="general-purpose"`.** Pick a specialist. If no specialist fits, do it directly at the top level rather than falling back to general-purpose.
- **Always pass `model="opus"`** on every Agent tool call.

## Coding standards

This project follows `codingStandards.md` (in the project root). That file is the ground truth for:

- Comments (never inline; always above the code).
- Data handling (no mock data, no testnet defaults, real implementations only).
- File management (edit existing scripts when debugging; don't create parallel copies).
- Workflow optimization (parallel tool invocation, reflect on results, clean up temp files).

Read `codingStandards.md` before any non-trivial change.

## Git workflow

- Commit and push all completed, verified, working changes.
- Verify before committing — run tests, exercise the code path.
- Use descriptive commit messages that explain *why*, not just *what*.
- **Never add `Co-Authored-By` lines for AI / Claude / any AI assistant.** Hard rule.

## Data handling

- No mock data.
- No testnet defaults.
- Real implementations or explicit declaration that the dependency isn't ready.

